<title>INDIA: Indian Grasim 96/97 net down.</title>
<headline>Indian Grasim 96/97 net down.</headline>
<dateline>BOMBAY 1997-04-30</dateline>
<text>
<p>Year to March 31, 1997.</p>
<p>	    (in million rupees unless stated)</p>
<p>    Net profit	    2,745.6   vs	 3,318.0</p>
<p>    Net sales	    30,866.1   vs	27,421.2</p>
<p>    Shr (in rupees)	 37.97   vs	   45.89</p>
<p>    Div (in rupees)	  6.50   vs	    6.25</p>
<p>    Gross profit	  4,631.0   vs	  5,434.6</p>
<p>    Depreciation	  1,475.4   vs	  1,239.1</p>
<p>    Tax			 410.0   vs	    877.5</p>
<p>Note - Grasim Industries Ltd, flagship of India's Aditya Birla group, said profits were hit by lower realisation in cement and depressed steel and textile markets.</p>
<p>It hopes to improve profits and sales in 1997/98 through higher volume growth and better efficiencies.</p>
<p>It expects to commission in the third quarter of 1997 a 30,000 tonnes a year viscose staple fibre (VSF) plant -- being the first phase of a 60,000 tonnes a year project in western Gujarat state, the firm said in a statement.</p>
<p>The company is India's largest producer of VSF, a raw material for textiles. It also makes textiles, sponge iron, cement and caustic soda.</p>
<p>Grasim raised $90 million and $100 million respectively in 1992 and 1994 through global depositary receipt issues overseas, but a third issue for $125 million had to be called off in 1996/97 due to poor market conditions.</p>
<p>--Bombay newsroom +91-22-265-9000</p>
